The paper deals with the theoretical aspects of Binary Decision Diagrams (BDDs) and Zero-suppressed BDDs (ZDDs), which are primarily used in computer science for efficient representation and manipulation of Boolean functions and sets of sets. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), followed by cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity). The paper also discusses functor structures, which are related to category theory, making cs.PL (Programming Languages) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with sentential decision diagrams, which are related to propositional logic, making cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) a possible sub-category as well.
